etrology. These include phase equilibria and the occurrences, chemistry, and petrology of micas in igneous, metamorphic, and sedimentary rocks, pegmatites, and certain ore deposits. Some treatments are exhaustive. All are at the forefront of our present knowledge, and indicate clearly the practical applications'of the study of micas to ascertaining various parameters of origin and crystallization history, as well as the many problems that still exist. The aim of this type of treatment is to provide a reference volume for teachers and students and to enable researchers to pick more easily those directions and problems for which future research is most needed or is apt to be most productive or most challenging.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 4aGlimmer. 4aIllit. 4aIonenaustausch. 4aKristallographie. 4aMineralogie. 7aSCIENCE / Earth Sciences / Mineralogy.2bisacsh1 aBailey, S. W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBailey, S.W., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBurt, Donald M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEberl, Dennis D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGiese Jr., R. F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuggenheim, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuidotti, Charles V., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHewitt, David A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMunoz, J. L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOdom, I. Edgar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRossman, George R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSpeer, J . Alexander, econtri